│ stop({"edit_points": [[326, 329,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlan.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding  │
│ the Issue: The crash occurs in VPTransformState::get when trying to         │
│ dereference an iterator that is a sentinel (end iterator). This happens     │
│ because LastInst is a terminator instruction (invoke) and                   │
│ std::next(BasicBlock::iterator(LastInst)) yields the end iterator. The code │
│ then attempts to dereference it via &*NewIP, causing an assertion           │
│ failure.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the vectorizer is  │
│ expanding SCEV %step, which is an invoke instruction in the entry block.    │
│ The expansion creates a scalar value for lane 0, which is the invoke        │
│ itself. Since the invoke is a terminator, the next iterator is the          │
│ sentinel.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The code in VPTransformState::get      │
│ assumes that LastInst is not a terminator when using std::next. However,    │
│ for uniform values that are live-in (like %step), the scalar value may be a │
│ terminator (e.g., invoke, callbr, etc.). The fix is to handle terminators   │
│ specially: if LastInst is a terminator, we should set the insert point      │
│ after the terminator? Actually, we cannot insert after a terminator because │
│ the block ends there. Instead, we should set the insert point to the        │
│ terminator's parent block's end (i.e., after the terminator). But we cannot │
│ insert after a terminator; we need to insert before it. However, the        │
│ purpose of setting the insert point is to broadcast the scalar value (which │
│ is uniform). Since the scalar value is already defined (the invoke), we can │
│ broadcast it in the preheader, not after the terminator. Indeed, the        │
│ GetBroadcastInstrs function already handles hoisting to the preheader when  │
│ safe. The issue is that we are trying to set the insert point after the     │
│ terminator, which is invalid.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s): Modify the      │
│ logic to avoid dereferencing the sentinel. When LastInst is a terminator,   │
│ we should set the insert point to the end of the block (i.e., before the    │
